{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657254"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:25:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19125"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19125"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81394"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11859"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19125"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66736"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28042"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81394"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESurgical procedures are often named using standardised Greek and Latin word elements. Understanding these elements helps in comprehending the nature of surgical procedures.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a surgical procedure where an incision is made into an organ without removal of tissue?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Procedure ending in -ostomy","Procedure ending in -otomy","Procedure ending in -plasty","Procedure ending in -pexy","Procedure ending in -ectomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprocedure ending in -otomy\u003C/strong\u003E involves making a surgical incision into an organ or structure without removing tissue. For example, gastrotomy (incision into the stomach) or thoracotomy (incision into the chest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcedure ending in -ectomy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to surgical removal of an organ or structure (e.g. appendectomy - removal of appendix)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcedure ending in -ostomy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to creating a new permanent or temporary opening or connection (e.g. colostomy - creating an opening from the colon to the skin surface)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcedure ending in -plasty\u003C/strong\u003E refers to surgical reconstruction or repair (e.g. rhinoplasty - reconstructive surgery of the nose)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcedure ending in -pexy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to surgical fixation of an organ (e.g. gastropexy - fixing the stomach in position)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these common surgical suffixes helps healthcare professionals quickly comprehend the general nature of a surgical procedure from its name.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The suffix -ectomy means surgical removal of an organ or structure","The suffix -otomy means surgical incision or cutting into an organ or structure","The suffix -ostomy means creating a surgical opening or new connection"],"references":["St John WA, Prefixes and Suffixes, https://clinical.stjohnwa.com.au/medical-library/medical-terminology/prefixes-and-suffixes"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66736"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19125"}},"stemMedia":{"d